A manual KNN

Imagine that we want to predict how much schnitzel would be eaten by a person who drank exactly three beers. A KNN learner will construct a prediction from the average of the nearest k training observationsâ \(y\) values. In this case, nearness is calculated only using \(x\). This is because we might not actually observe \(y\) in the real world: remember weâre focused primarly on making predictions in Data Science, and sometimes we might want to make predictions about things that havenât happened yet!

So, thinking about a prediction for someone who drank exactly three beers, we can think of the following plot:

If we had trained a \(k=1\) learner, then we would pick only the nearest observation to 3 beers, and predict that the schnitzel eaten by someone who drank 3 beers is exactly the amount of schnitzel eaten by someone who drank the nearest to 3 beers. This is observation \(1\) in the plot above, which has a value of 94 grams. However, if we picked the nearest \(k=4\) observations:

beer schnitzel d
3.04 94 0.04
2.89 99 0.11
2.86 105 0.14
2.78 96 0.22

Our average would instead be 98.5 grams. In fact, our predicted value for someone who drinks three beers really strongly depends on \(k\); as you increase \(k\), your prediction generally increases:

This is because the points that are nearest to 3 beers are have relatively low schnitzel consumption. The points that are very far from 3 have much higher schnitzel consumption.

Comprehension Check
  1. What is the predicted schnitzel value when \(k=n\)? What does that value represent? This represents the average schnitzel consumption for people at oktoberfest. This is because the average of the nearest observations is just the average of all the observations!
  2. Why do we see a big jump when nearness_cutoff\(=15\)? This is a tie. You can see in the preceeding plot, two observations are labelled as 15.5, meaning that they share the 15 and 16 ranks between them. This means that once you go from \(k=14\) to \(k=15\), you have to pick one of those two observations to use for your average. And, it also means you âjumpâ two observations in one step of the nearness cutoff.

Thinking about KNN curves

Below, we can visualize what the predicted schnizel consumption is when you pick different values of \(k\). For each of these curves, we just follow a very simple rule.

  1. find a location on the \(x\) axis
  2. find the \(k\) observations that have the most similar \(x\) values
  3. calculate the average \(y\) value for these \(k\) observations
  4. this average is your prediction for \(y\).

Note that, for now, weâre assuming that weâre just using the standard average, so our prediction function changes as a âstepâ each time a new observation enters, or leaves, the \(k\)-nearest neighbor set. If we scan across the \(x\) axis from left to right, you can see each jump as a location where this happens. More advanced applications of KNN instead use a weighted average of the nearest \(k\) observations, such that observations that are closer to our prediction point have more weight.1

Weâll use these functions to think through the following questions:

Comprehension Check
  1. Why do the KNN learners âflatten outâ at the very small and very big values of beer? Because there are no new observations out past these values. Once you get to the edge of the point cloud, no new information is provided as a function of getting more extreme. So, the KNN learner just continues to predict the same value.
  2. Which KNN learner do you think has the lowest error? \(k=1\)passes through each point exactly, and so clearly has the lowest possible error of zero.
  3. Which KNN learner do you think represents the best tradeoff in terms of the bias-variance tradeoff? I think that \(k=4\) has the best traedoff here. Itâs fairly smooth visually, but still manages to follow the point cloud effectively.

Use the plot to approximately judge which model would have the best performance on this validation set. Again working visually, I look at 1 and follow it up to the value 127. Then, I look at 2 and follow it up to 127 again, and the same for \((3.98\) and \((4,225)\). I personally think visually, it either \(k=4\) or \(k=12\) would be best. The \(k=4\) model seems to be too high for small beer values, while \(k=12\) is definitely too high for \(3\) and \(4\) beers.

Training a KNN learner yourself

To optimize our KNN learner using crossvalidation, we can use the caret package. This is a general-purpose interface to nearly any estimator you would want to use. This is the table of the 238 (at the time of writing) estimators supported by caret. To fit a KNN, you set method=knn.

library(caret)

knn = train(
    schnitzel ~ beer, 
    data=oktoberfest, 
    method='knn', 
    trControl=trainControl(method='cv')
)

By default, caret will try to find a âgoodâ value of \(k\), but it often will not search enough values. To find a good value, you may need to specify the tuneGrid option. This option takes a dataframe of parameter values for which you want to check the fit:

library(caret)

knn = train(
    schnitzel ~ beer, 
    data=oktoberfest, 
    method='knn', 
    trControl=trainControl(method='cv'), 
    tuneGrid=data.frame(k=1:18)
)
Warning in nominalTrainWorkflow(x = x, y = y, wts = weights, info = trainInfo,
: There were missing values in resampled performance measures.
Note

As a general rule, if the âbestâ parameter you find sits at the very biggest (or very smallest), you may need to increase (or decrease) the upper (or lower) limit of the values youâre searching! For KNN, \(k>0\), so you can at least stop the search when \(k=1\).

Objects fit using caret::train() always show a results table that contains many of the common scores/losses you might want to consider. Showing the first three rows:

knn$results |> head(3) |> knitr::kable()
k RMSE Rsquared MAE RMSESD RsquaredSD MAESD
1 16.09129 0.9141400 13.81667 13.19317 0.2135856 11.080917
2 15.63396 0.8065457 13.04167 12.25048 0.3377557 9.036726
3 17.19469 0.8188439 14.59306 11.25798 0.3523562 8.457866

This makes it easy to plot the accuracy of the learner as a function of \(k\):

ggplot(knn$results, aes(x=k, y=RMSE)) + 
    geom_line() + geom_point()

From this plot, you might think that choosing any \(k<6\) is fairly defensible. By default, caret picks the model with the best RMSE and stores it under the finalModel attribute:

knn$finalModel
2-nearest neighbor regression model

The caret::train() function picks models with the lowest RMSE by default. This might not always pick the same model as other loss/gain functions. For example, we would pick a different model if we wanted to optimize our R-squared:

ggplot(knn$results, aes(x=k, y=Rsquared)) + 
    geom_line() + geom_point()

You can switch to other gain functions using the maximize argument:

knn_abs = train(
    schnitzel ~ beer, 
    data=oktoberfest, 
    method='knn',
    metric="Rsquared",
    maximize = TRUE,
    trControl=trainControl(method='cv'), 
    tuneGrid=data.frame(k=1:18)
)
Warning in nominalTrainWorkflow(x = x, y = y, wts = weights, info = trainInfo,
: There were missing values in resampled performance measures.
knn_abs$finalModel
8-nearest neighbor regression model
Note

Note that the exact value of \(k\) can change depending on the random changes between cross-validation splits. Try proving this to yourself by training a knn model twice using the same options. In large data, this generally averages out, but to ensure you get the same results every time, make sure to give the set.seed() a number, like your student number, your birthday, or some other number, to ensure that the randomness is the same every time. Usually, we set the seed once at the start, or once per chunk if youâre repeating that chunk over and over again to troubleshoot.

You can use this model to make predictions, too:

new_data = tibble(beer=1:4)
preds = predict(knn$finalModel, new_data)

new_data |> mutate(prediction=preds) |> knitr::kable()
beer prediction

3 96.5
4 221.0

for(k in c(1,4,12,23)){

    predy_test = predict(model, newdata=known_results)

}

Common pitfalls with KNN

One common issue with KNN learners is that they are interpolators. That is, a KNN learner will never predict outside of the range of \(y\) that has been observed. Many common models, such as random forests and decision trees which we will consider later in this unit, are also interpolators. These algorithms are often very good at achieving high accuracy when predicting inside of the range of the observed \(y\) variable, but are generally unreliable for forecasting.

Another common issue with KNN learners is that they do not handle categorical predictors well. A KNN algorithm can easily make predictions about categorical variables, but they have a hard time dealing with categorical \(x\) variables. This is because of the issue of ties. Imagine youâre predicting the price of a car based on its color. You have five âredâ cars, seven âgreenâ cars, and ten âblueâ cars, all worth different prices. When \(k=3\) and youâre predicting about a âblueâ car, which of the ten training points do you pick? All of them? Then, itâs not a âknnâ learner! If you want to be strict about \(k\), you then must pick \(k\) values at random when predicting a value for a âblueâ car when \(k\) is smaller than the number of observations within a group. Second, imagine if \(k=8\) and youâre predicting the value of a green car. Is âredâ closer to âgreenâ than âblackâ? If you canât decide, then do you pick at random from the âredâ cars? or the âblackâ cars? or, do you pick randomly from all of the red and black cars? At its core, KNN learners work best when distance is a natural, simple-to-interpret function on the \(x\) variables. For categorical \(x\) or \(x\) with many ties, this is often not the case, and this will make predictions based on a KNN learner less useful.

Another common issue with KNN is that they are scale sensitive. This means that the \(k\) value that is discovered depends on the magnitude of \(x\). This is not a problem when there is only one predictor, but as soon as there is more than one predictor, this can become a problem.

Comprehension check

    3. What is the standard deviation of the lstat feature? How about the age feature? SD of lstat is about 7.14, while age is up at 28.14
    4. If a test point is 1 unit away from a training point in model (a), whatâs the largest difference in age between the test point and the training point? How about lstat? if a test point is 1 unit of distance away, itâs either one year older (or younger) or itâs one percentage point different on the lower socioeconomic status population in the area, which is what lstat measures.
    5. If a test point is 1 unit away from a training point in model (b), whatâs the largest difference in age between the test point and training point? How about lstat? If a test point is 1 unit away from a training point in model (b), whatâs the largest difference in age between the test point and training point? How about lstat? Here, now that weâve standardized the input data, a unit difference in the distance means the house is twenty eight years apart, or itâs seven percentage points different on the lower socioeconomic status population percentage.
    6. Given what you learned about (d) and (e), is the model from part (a) more sensitive to age or lstat? How about the model in part (b)? the model from part a will be more sensitive to changes in age because the variability in age changes more slowly as a function of distance. Put another way, observations are more likely to be close on their lstat feature because its variance/standard deviation is so much smaller than the age feature. This means that an overall distance between two observations in the first model has a small amount âcausedâ by differences in lstat, but much more âcausedâ by differences in age. So, two houses that are âsimilarâ will tend to be quite similar in age, but less similar on the lstat feature. In model b, a unit of distance corresponds to a standard deviation change in either input variable, so model b will listen to both of them equally.
